{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fe43bfc6-8011-4ffc-9809-7d5b27a14555","content":"## What happened\n\n`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because **Apple's Security.framework has never implemented DSA**, and .NET relies on the platform's native crypto libraries. In earlier versions .NET may have silently fallen back to an OpenSSL-based shim on macOS, but .NET 11 removed that fallback, aligning with the `SYSLIB0028` obsolescence warnings that have been on `DSA` since .NET 7.\n\nOn Linux (`DSAOpenSsl` → system OpenSSL) and Windows (`DSACng`) the native libraries still support DSA, so those platforms keep working.\n\n## How to fix\n\nSince you only need to **verify** existing legacy signatures, use a managed (cross-platform) DSA implementation such as **BouncyCastle**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the platform-dependent call:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (.NET 10) — throws on macOS in .NET 11\nusing var dsa = DSA.Create();\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(spki, out _);\nbool ok = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n```\n\n```csharp\n// After — works everywhere via managed code\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar pubKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(spki);          // DsaPublicKeyParameters\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool ok = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n**Longer-term**, migrate callers to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** — both are supported natively on all three platforms and are not deprecated.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d2cee5fb-4622-4ac6-9860-a63772853094","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue related to DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason through this based on my knowledge of .NET's cryptography evolution.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET's handling of DSA on macOS. Let me explain what happened.\n\nThe key issue: Apple's macOS/iOS security frameworks (Security.framework / CommonCrypto) have been deprecating older cryptographic algorithms. DSA is considered legacy and insecure. .NET on macOS uses Apple's native crypto libraries (via the `System.Security.Cryptography` implementation that delegates to platform APIs).\n\n\n.NET has been progressively phasing out legacy cryptographic algorithms, and DSA support on macOS has been particularly problematic since Apple's Security framework doesn't provide robust DSA support in newer versions. The trajectory suggests that .NET 11 likely removed or further restricted DSA functionality, especially on macOS where platform-level support is already limited.\n\nIf DSA is no longer available, the practical options are to use a cross-platform library like BouncyCastle for signature verification if you're not creating new signatures, or migrate to modern algorithms like ECDSA or Ed25519 entirely. DSA support on macOS was likely handled through an OpenSSL fallback in .NET 10, which got removed in .NET 11 as part of a broader shift away from DSA. This aligns with .NET's security direction of deprecating weaker algorithms. macOS doesn't support DSA through Apple's native crypto APIs, so `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If it worked in .NET 10, they might have been explicitly using `DSAOpenSsl` with OpenSSL installed, or relying on a different code path that's no longer available.\n\nFor a real solution, I'd recommend using BouncyCastle.Cryptography for cross-platform DSA support, or better yet, migrating to ECDSA or Ed25519 since DSA is legacy and being deprecated across .NET versions.","outputTokens":1989,"requestId":"6C29:149CB5:E56C2C:10D0E7B:69FE9315"},"id":"9a358418-c267-4711-88a3-0f52881ec508","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:51:59.131Z","parentId":"1708f501-d249-4120-8084-a2949b2a625d"}
